  "What is centripetal force?": "",
  "The force that speeds up objects in circular motion": "",
  "A specific type of force, like gravity or friction": "",
  "A force that acts outward from the center": "",
  "The net force directed toward the center of the circular path that causes circular motion: F_c = mv²/r": "",
  "Centripetal force is not a new type of force; it is the net inward force that maintains circular motion. It can be provided by gravity, tension, friction, normal force, or any combination.": "",
  "What does 'centripetal' literally mean?": "",
  "Force-generating": "",
  "Circle-making": "",
  "Center-seeking": "",
  "Center-fleeing": "",
  "'Centripetal' comes from Latin roots meaning 'center-seeking.' The centripetal force is always directed toward the center of the circular path.": "",
  "What is the formula for centripetal force?": "",
  "F_c = mv²r, directed toward the center": "",
  "F_c = mv/r², directed away from the center": "",
  "F_c = mv²/r = mω²r, directed toward the center of the circle": "",
  "F_c = mrω, directed tangent to the circle": "",
  "Centripetal force F_c = mv²/r = mω²r, always directed radially inward toward the center of the circular path.": "",
  "What provides the centripetal force for a car turning on a flat road?": "",
  "The normal force from the road": "",
  "The car's engine": "",
  "Kinetic friction": "",
  "Static friction between the tires and the road": "",
  "On a flat road, static friction between the tires and road surface provides the inward centripetal force needed for the car to follow the curved path.": "",
  "What is the purpose of banking a curve?": "",
  "To increase the friction force": "",
  "To increase the speed limit on the curve": "",
  "To reduce the weight of vehicles on the curve": "",
  "To tilt the normal force so its horizontal component provides centripetal force, reducing reliance on friction": "",
  "Banking tilts the normal force inward, so its horizontal component provides (or assists with) the centripetal force. At the design speed, no friction is needed.": "",
  "What is the 'critical speed' at the top of a vertical loop?": "",
  "The speed at which centripetal force equals gravity": "",
  "The minimum speed at the top where the normal force (or tension) just becomes zero: v_c = sqrt(rg)": "",
  "The speed at which friction provides all the centripetal force": "",
  "The maximum speed before the track breaks": "",
  "At critical speed, gravity alone provides the centripetal force (N = 0): mg = mv²/r, giving v_c = sqrt(rg). Below this speed, the object loses contact.": "",
